This not only confirms that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely held, but provides details that fossils generally cannot, such as color and three-dimensional disposition.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was brownish-châtain on the upper side and pale or carotenoid on the underside.
This discovery also allows for a better understanding of the evolution of feathers in birds.
Since dinosaur feathers do not have an entirely developed stem, called a rachis, but do show other feather-like characteristics - barbs and barbels - researchers have concluded that the rachis was probably an evolutionary development later than these other characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used in flight but rather for temperature regulation or display. The researchers suggested that, even though it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen shows an adult plumage and not the duvet of a young one.
The scientists say that it is certainly the tail of a juvenile dinosaur, but the specimen reveals a plumage belonging to an adult individual, and not to a juvenile.
